128. 19. pietas oui coniuncta iustitia est. Pietas according to the 2513 definition given 1, 41, 116 is itself iustitia adversum deos. reliquaeque virtutes refers to the connection of ali the virtues one with another, the coniunctio confusioque virtutum as Cicero says De Fin. V, 23, 67, which is often mentioned as a cardinal principle oi the Stoic ethical philosophy. Comp. Diog.Laert.VII,125: τὰς δὲ ἀρετὰς λέγουσιν ἀντακολουθεῖν ἀλλή- leus, καὶ τὸν μίαν ἔχοντα πάσας ἔχειν.

128. 20. par et similis. These expressions are frequently used to· gether to express complete similarity in every respect. The difference between them is that par indicates the valae, importance or power of a thing, similis its constitution, external or internal. Quintilian X, 1, 102 speaking oi Sallust and Livy says that they were pares magis quam similes, ie. equal in worth, though different in character; and Seneca De Ira 1, 9 speaking oi the passions says: quas (affectus) numquam deprimere passis, nisi pares illis similesque opposueris, ie. passions equally strong and like in kind.
